##Interrupted Future: Can I get a job with an epidemic like that?

Micro-signal Jianjiaobuluo

Function description, pepper tribe, amplify your voice! Chinese Women Workers Exclusive Information Platform, you are welcome to pay attention!

ABSTRACT: This article is a contribution to the "2020, our life is continuing" essay contest. 2020 was supposed to be a year of transformation. With the outbreak, everything became a question mark.

As the days of not being able to go out grew longer, so did my anxiety about unemployment.
Today, I'm in my fifth week of sitting at home on my phone.
This sudden outbreak interrupted all of my plans to be in Florida when an offline course was canceled and a planned transition to a new job was halted. Now, in order to avoid being infected with the epidemic, I had to hide in the house, helplessly waiting for the news of improvement. All those expectations of the future have become a huge question mark.
It's like a butterfly, completely bound, trying to spread its wings, but unable to fly.

When the news of the outbreak came pouring in,
On January 17th, I finished my studies and flew back from abroad.
Before this, because of being out of town, coupled with heavy school work, I do not pay attention to domestic information, also do not know some local news events. I just stick to the original plan, come back and Family New Year, and then after the Lantern Festival, continue to go out to finish the last week of classes, and then enter the busy state of job hunting.
This year, it should be no different than the past new year, I think. Looking at the street full of beautiful New Year goods, and have been trying to call the vendors, I can not help feeling: "another year. " At this time, I do not know in the following month, the dream will always appear this prosperous, vibrant scene.

Photograph: DRIBBBLE.COM/URANCD  
After a day of rest at home, I finally opened up my social media platform and wondered if anything new or interesting had happened in the country while I was missing out on information. But everywhere I looked, there were messages for help, and I suddenly realized the severity of the epidemic. But I looked for a long time, but can not find a detailed report, there is no clear data, can only continue to pay attention and wait.
On the 19th, I went out to meet friends and talked about the epidemic. My friend told me that he also saw relevant information, and now the Spring Festival travel is in progress, do not know the extent of the disease will develop, very worrying. However, friends also a little lucky, after all, it is only "Wuhan Pneumonia" , from our living environment so far away, should not have any danger.
After listening to my friend's share, my mood lightened a little. But I am still in a state of partial knowledge of the epidemic. The questions of whether to buy enough masks, and what type of masks to avoid, and how to avoid fake masks, are popping up in my head like firecrackers.
On the 20th, however,. As requests for help grew, videos were forwarded and blocked on social media platforms, and contagion and death became the key words of the day. I began to get nervous, repeating to my family the severity of the outbreak, what supplies we needed, and how little we needed to get out of the house.
Information is slowly growing, and even flocking to me. I didn't know for sure, and I didn't know how to tell the difference, so I just kept my eyes open.

A quiet new year and empty streets
After that day, I had to cancel all the New Year's parties I had planned with my friends. All human contact, as restaurants, bars, cinemas and other social venues closed, from offline to online, in order to maintain each other's feelings.
My sleep time became later and later, and my daily life became reversed day and night. As soon as I wake up, it's almost noon, and I start looking at all kinds of reports, figures, pictures and videos on my phone. Sometimes when I look, I see the wee hours. Other than my family waking me up for dinner, I spent the rest of the day skimming through information about the outbreak.
A sense of panic, born of ignorance about the disease, is slowly filling the minds and bodies of ordinary people. In one video I saw, people, whether they had a mild cold or were actually infected with pneumonia, were crowded in a hospital in Wuhan, waiting for doctors to diagnose and treat them. The fragility of the human race is evident in that scene.
At the same time, I also noticed that the medical staff in the case of inadequate supplies, but still remain at their posts. In the videos that were later deleted, a nurse screams "I don't want to die, either, " but the truth is so cruel that it's a hellish, protracted battle.
But I am even more concerned that this precious information, worth storing in history and in everyone's memory, will soon be expunged on the grounds that it is false. Dense information, but also from the moment of free discussion into a screen after a blank. The absence of these words, pictures, will also make everyone more about how to live next, have more doubts.

In addition to putting up with the powerlessness of not circulating information, I joined my friends and family in counseling and popularizing science. Because the family elders do not like to watch the News, the outbreak of knowledge is not much, go out still do not wear a mask. To this end, some friends opened a chat group to discuss the matter, and produced a lot of elderly people in line with the reading of the article and video, to remind the family of the current severity of the epidemic.
Slowly, I could no longer bear the impact of the epidemic, and began to cry, unable to stop looking at information, and crying as I did, as if I was in love with both the patients and the staff. Occasionally, I would take the initiative to voice chat with friends, trying to share some interesting things and experiences, so that I could pull myself out of the epidemic. But after a while, people start to sigh and talk about information that makes them sad or angry.
The younger generation, not only physically trapped at home, growing up in a cage; even our sense of citizenship, because we can not speak, can only be imprisoned in their own minds.
Finally, I couldn't resist going out. The streets were empty except for a few scattered people. The Noisy Spring Festival in the past, has now become a calm, let me in this already cold winter, more sad. The song, repeated every year from street to street, is now sounding like a humble Kung Hei fat choi: to be in good health.
I never thought I would have such a Cold New Year in my lifetime.

When life becomes a big question mark
2020 was supposed to be my year of transformation.
Before returning to China, I applied for a research course for a week, after the Spring Festival. But now that the classes have been canceled, the visas are useless. It is not known whether the course will be reopened after the outbreak. I even regret that if I had not returned home, I might not now need to cry at home every day, trapped in anxiety and grief.
But those who stayed told me that it would not be easy to come back even before the outbreak was particularly severe. Because isolation is such a small thing, it is most difficult to endure as a differential treatment. In the early days of the epidemic, many people in Wuhan, even in Hubei Province, were treated as though pneumonia itself had been pushed aside and ignored. They, too, are left in foreign lands to be spurned by strangers for their accents.

The cancellation was just the beginning, and my career transition was cut short.
After three years as a freelancer, I want to change my environment, go to a new field of work, and meet some new friends. I prepared a resume, ready to finish school, choose to be a "social animal. ". Maybe I'll have a hard time putting up with workplace struggles, or working overtime every day, or even horrible workplace sexism. But I'm all set, and with unlimited expectations for 2020, I want to redefine my status and identity.
But the epidemic has utterly and inexorably crushed that vision. For the past month, I haven't been able to go out and think. Just walk from the room to the living room, or from the kitchen to the bathroom. The only place I can feel is in the small space of the balcony, basked in the warm afternoon sun, which can restore some strength.
So just wait. Is it GONNA be okay?
Many industries, many companies and even self-employed people who should have made a lot of money around the Spring Festival due to the unexpected epidemic are now unable to continue their operations due to lack of funds. Will they be able to provide jobs and pay salaries after the outbreak?
Moreover, even if you go out to look for a job now, you will have to go back to work for an indefinite period of time in each city, face a self imposed isolation of 14 days, and find a house to rent, and you are not sure whether you will be thrown out of the community -- into every aspect of your life, has become a giant question mark.
I am not Haizi, but now I can only hope that they can face the sea, feel the spring flowers open.

#When life becomes a big question mark

It is not known whether the course will be reopened after the outbreak. I even regret that if I had not returned home, I might not now need to cry at home every day, trapped in anxiety and grief.

". Maybe I'll have a hard time putting up with workplace struggles, or working overtime every day, or even horrible workplace sexism. I am not Haizi, but now I can only hope that they can face the sea, feel the spring flowers open.
